"Weaver R.L.S., Steffen K., Heinrighs J.","Data assimilation in sea-ice monitoring",2000,"Annals of Glaciology","31",,,"327","332",,,,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-0034512265&partnerID=40&md5=1305dffb20c0ce52e37cbb902a92e06f","Cooperative Inst. Res. Envi. Sci., University of Colorado, Department of Geosciences, Boulder CO 80309, United States","Weaver, R.L.S., Cooperative Inst. Res. Envi. Sci., University of Colorado, Department of Geosciences, Boulder CO 80309, United States; Steffen, K., Cooperative Inst. Res. Envi. Sci., University of Colorado, Department of Geosciences, Boulder CO 80309, United States; Heinrighs, J., Cooperative Inst. Res. Envi. Sci., University of Colorado, Department of Geosciences, Boulder CO 80309, United States","The derection of small changes in concetration or thickness in the Arctic or Antarctic ice cover is an important topic in the current global-climate-change debate. Change detection using satellite data alone requires rigorous error analysis for their derived ice products, including inter-satellite validation for long time series. All models of physical processes are only approximations, and the best models of complicated physical processes have errors and uncertainties. A promising approach is data assimilation, combining model, in situ data and satellite remote-sensing data. Sea-ice monitoring from satellite, ice-model estimates, and the potential benefit of combining the two are discussed in some detail. In a case-study we demonstrate how the sea-ice backscatter for the Beaufort Sea region was derived using a backscattering model in combination with an ice model. We conclude that, for data assimilation, the first steps include the use of simple models, moving, with success at this level, to progressively more complex models. We also recommend reconfiguring the current remote-sensing data to include precise time tags with each pixel. For example, the current Special Sensor Microwave Imager data might be reissued in a time-tagged orbital (or gridded) format as opposed to the currently available daily averaged gridded data. Finally, error statistics and quality-control information also need to be readily available in a form useful for assimilation. The effectiveness of data-assimilation techniques is directly linked to the availability of data error statistics.",,"data assimilation; ice thickness; monitoring; remote sensing; sea ice",,,,,,"Agnew, T.A., Le, H., Hirose, T., Estimation of large-scale sea-ice motion from SSM/I 85.5 GHz imagery (1997) Ann. Glaciol, 25, pp. 305-311; Cavalieri, D.J., Parkinson, C.L., Gloersen, P., Zwally, H.J., Arctic and Antarctic sea ice concentrations from multichannel passive-microwave satellite data sets: October 1978 to September 1995. User's guide (1997) NASA Tech. Memo, p. 104647; Cheng, A., Preller, R., An ice-ocean coupled model for the Northern Hemisphere (1992) Geophys. Res. Lett, 19 (9), pp. 901-904; Comiso, J.C., Kwok, R., Surface and radiative characteristics of the summer Arctic sea ice cover from multi-sensor satellite observations (1996) J. Geophys. Res, 101 C (12), pp. 28397-28416; Crutcher, H.L., Meserve, J.M., (1970) Selected Level Heights, Temperatures and Dew Points for the Northern Hemisphere, , Revised edition. Washington, DC, U.S. Navy. Weather Service Command. (NAVAIR Report 50-1C-52.); Flato, G.M., Hibler III, W.D., Ridging and strength in modeling the thickness distribution of Arctic sea ice (1995) J. Geophys. Res, 100 C (9), pp. 18611-18626; Hibler III, W.D., A dynamic thermodynamic sea ice model (1979) J. Phys. Oceanogr, 9 (7), pp. 815-846; Hibler III, W.D., Bryan, K., A diagnostic ice-ocean model (1987) J. Phys. Oceanogr, 17 (7), pp. 987-1015; Hibler III, W.D., Walsh, J.E., On modeling seasonal and interannual fluctuations of Arctic sea ice (1982) J. Phys. Oceanogr, 12 (12), pp. 1514-1523; Kwok, R., Baltzer, T., The geophysical processor system at the Alaska-SAR-facility (1995) Photogramm. Eng. Remote Sensing, 61 